<div id="review_2151913256" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2151913256" />
    <a title="T&#39;leah" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7175972-t-leah"><img alt="T&#39;leah" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1555512647p2/7175972.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2151913256?book_show_action=true">Oct 16, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="T&#39;leah" class="user" itemprop="url" name="T&#39;leah" href="/user/show/7175972-t-leah">T&#39;leah</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/24500681-on-herring-cove-road">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2151913256" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4168739758406590711">So the title: <br/>The book starts with Avriel Rosen, an elderly Jewish gentleman, leaving his house for work extra early to avoid the blue-eyed blond haired neighbor boy greeting him as &quot;Mr. Jew.&quot; He thinks of wanting to respond with &quot;Goy Boy&quot; but his wife wouldn&apos;t approve of that language. But you find out fairly fast it&apos;s all one big misunderstanding, which I won&apos;t spoil for you because it&apos;s rather cute. <br/><br/>And that explains this novel. It&apos;s rather cute. There&apos;s some deep moments, a few stray tears, </span>
  <span id="freeText4168739758406590711" style="display:none">So the title: <br />The book starts with Avriel Rosen, an elderly Jewish gentleman, leaving his house for work extra early to avoid the blue-eyed blond haired neighbor boy greeting him as "Mr. Jew." He thinks of wanting to respond with "Goy Boy" but his wife wouldn't approve of that language. But you find out fairly fast it's all one big misunderstanding, which I won't spoil for you because it's rather cute. <br /><br />And that explains this novel. It's rather cute. There's some deep moments, a few stray tears, but mostly just a lighthearted slice of life. Avriel is a British WW2 veteran who moves to Canada with his wife in order to flee reminders of a war that completely changed his personality. This novel focuses when he's in his 60s, and is mostly about Avriel cracking out of his shell. Those around him, his wife, the neighbor Lisa, her 9-year-old son Dewey, and her bigot husband Paul, have various impacts on his life, but he is by far the main character. <br /><br />So if you like cute little slice of life stories, this is a good read. Nothing too deep, nothing too complicated, just a good short little feel-good story with some not-so-feel-good moments in it. I read heavy fantasy, so it was a good little brain clearer in between trilogies.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4168739758406590711" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


